--- body ---
## Problem

Both housekeeping and pick-ticket use `grep -E "Status:" tickets/*.erg` to filter
tickets, then re-read each file individually. This loads raw file content into the
LLM context unnecessarily. `erg ready --json` already does this filtering in Go.

## Solution

Replace the grep+read pattern with a single `erg ready --json` call that returns
structured data (ticket id, title, status, blocked-by) — the LLM only sees what
it needs to make a decision, not full file content.

## Acceptance criteria

- `housekeeping` and `pick-ticket` use `erg ready --json` as the first ticket filter
- Individual ticket files are only read for candidates that pass the filter
- Token count for ticket scanning step reduced vs baseline

## Effort

Low — mostly skill prompt edits, no new infrastructure.

## Actions (planned)

1. `skills/ticket-ready/SKILL.md`: Replace "Read all tickets/*.erg files" step
   with `erg ready --json` as PRIMARY method. Keep manual read as fallback only
   if erg binary absent. Remove "Alternative" framing.
2. `skills/pick-ticket/SKILL.md`: After Step 1 (/ticket-ready), add explicit
   instruction to only read individual ticket files for candidates that need
   sweep-skip cache verification (body hash check). Do NOT read all bodies.
3. `skills/healthcheck/SKILL.md`: In docs freshness / ticket cross-check, add
   note to use `erg ready --json` for the initial ticket list instead of reading
   all files. Only read specific tickets whose status contradicts a doc reference.
4. Run tests, validate tickets, commit
